rComments: Personable - highly recommend getting to know her as a person. It makes her lecture discussions much more interesting. It's clear she wants her students to do well, and is very understanding of varying circumstances that affect students. Definitely would take again. Expect to integrate all the information, as in all of Dockstader's courses/exams.

She's one of the most amazing professors at uoft. She tailors courses to build unique skills for student success - whether thats creating a research poster in a regular lab course (HMB310) or being able to dabble in several different neuroimaging softwares (JHA410). Her response speed to emails is incredible and is so welcoming in office hours.

Great professor, very clear with instructions. However, she says ALOT of stuff, this course is very heavy. But if you study you'll do well questions are straight forward on exams and marking is very fair. One of the best profs in HMB!

Had Dockstader for HMB310 and HMB420. Extremely clear rubric. My scientific writing has improved dramatically. I found that her courses take a lot of work but you get so much out of it. Very helpful at office hours. Treats her students like human beings instead of numbers and it makes for an awesome experience. Must take for all neuro students!

Lab reports are marked confusingly and veryy time consuming. There ISN'T a clear grading criteria. Prof says one thing and TAs say another thing. She's a decent prof but plays favourites just like other HMB profs. Tests are fair, material is interesting. Not the course to take if you want an smooth A+ . Would not take again.

She is a great professor. One thing I really like enjoy is her interactive teaching style. She treats everyone as equals, which is really empowering. She is VERY approachable outside of class. Assignments and tests marked decently fairly. Tests in this course are very straight forward and fair. Overall, good person and prof!
teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Gives good feedback', 'Accessible outside class']

rComments: I am willing to get criticized but my efforts are not appreciated as much. Dont take this course if u dont like writing heavy papers, and be prepared to learn everything by yourself. Its better to have some lab experience to take this course
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Tough grader', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Dockstader is by far a wonderful lecturer and professor, overall. She certainly cares about her students, and while the content of her lectures may be a little less thorough than you'd expect, she will always take the time to go back to any unclear or confusing concepts. Inspirational story, individual, and professor. Def top notch in HMB!
I loved her teaching because it was straightforward and she really does care about the class. Would totally take another with class with her if I had the opportunity to.

By far one of the worst courses I've taken at U of T. Vague and hypocritical grading criteria, TAs who don't care about your learning experience, only giving grades that will abide by their marking curve. TAs didn't respond to my emails, even after taking my reports to the writing center, I saw no difference in grading. Left me feeling helpless.

The amount of effort you put into this course is not at all related to how well you will do. Dockstader was so unclear, unapproachable, and unhelpful. The course in general was not well designed - we had a lab about pipetting in a third year lab course - and was even more poorly taught. Do yourself a favor: steer clear of this course and this prof

She is one of the most interactive profs I've ever had. A very academic person with lots of connections. Expects a lot but is willing to work with you and do absolutely everything she can to help you get there. She slides are extremely useful and helpful for future reference as well; put things that will actually help you in the future.

She is a great prof. Keeps up with the most updated research and tries to be very interactive with the students, which is something that you don't see often in U of T. She's very clear about what she expects and easy to approach. She has high expectations BUT if you talk to her about your work & follow her grading scheme you can easily get an A.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Clear grading criteria', 'Accessible outside class']

rComments: She is confused all the time. She doesn't know how to respond to many questions. she is very unorganized and her questions are meant to trick you and check your technicality and not your knowledge. wouldnt take another class with her EVER!
Fantastic professor who tries to learn everybody's names and keep up with the current science. She treats students like colleagues and has cool lectures and assignments as well as fair tests.

Dockstader's knowledge seems pretty shaky in neuro. Too many guest lectures, confusing and too many mistakes. Wouldn't have taken it except the marks were rediculously easy. Final exam was a nightmare since she is unorganized. Her voice is annoying as hell too. Not the worse prof but not close to being good iether

She is really helpful. I liked her slides which were straight to the point. The course had a few overarching themes (such as how certain neurodevelopmental deficits can lead to a diseased state later on) but once you understand those, everything else falls into place. She is also the fastest and most helpful email responder I've ever met.
